Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]},{"name":"\"Ade\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which originated as a nickname from a word denoting something round and lumpish. It is one of several given names that owe their origin to their use for a character in  Margaret Mitchell's  novel Gone with the Wind (  1936 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Kade","meanings":["Respelling of   Cade ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adèle \"Ade\" de Picquigny was born in 1138, in Picquigny, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, her father, Guermond de Picquigny I, was 69 and her mother, Béatrice de Daours, was 47. She had at least 2 sons with Aleaume d'Amiens. She died in 1187, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1138–1187":"1138–1187","1083–1138":"1083–1138","1116–1178":"1116–1178","1128–1176":"1128–1176","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1151–1194":"1151–1194","1070–1131":"1070–1131","1091–1144":"1091–1144","about 1150":"umbes 1150","1091":"1091","1176":"1176","1187":"1187","1131":"1131","1151":"1151","1194":"1194","1150":"1150","1083":"1083","1070":"1070","1128":"1128","1138":"1138","1116":"1116","1178":"1178","1144":"1144","Picquigny, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Picquigny, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Daours, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Daours, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa","Amiens, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Amiens, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1138–1187":"1138–1187","1083–1138":"1083–1138","1116–1178":"1116–1178","1128–1176":"1128–1176","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","1151–1194":"1151–1194","1070–1131":"1070–1131","1091–1144":"1091–1144","about 1150":"noin 1150","1091":"1091","1176":"1176","1187":"1187","1131":"1131","1151":"1151","1194":"1194","1150":"1150","1083":"1083","1070":"1070","1128":"1128","1138":"1138","1116":"1116","1178":"1178","1144":"1144","Picquigny, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Picquigny, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Ranska","Daours, Somme, Hauts-d